mat the session URL and display lifecycle updates, then test the disabled gate path, successful flow, and how archive failures surface as warnings.\n\nNow I'm thinking through where the session ID contract test should live—the service layer just passes the session ID through without modification, so I could either put the test in the remote-runtime crate where the normalization functions already exist, or create a service-level contract test in the application crate that verifies the ID is preserved end-to-end.\n\nFor the acceptance tests, I'll verify that the session ID from the service response matches what the mock client returned and that the service doesn't alter it. I'm also planning to add some rendering helper functions for CLI output—one for the bridge disabled message, one for the session URL, one for lifecycle state updates, and one for archive warnings. Then I'll start implementing the bridge mode acceptance tests using the same imports and patterns from the existing remote session service tests.\n\nSetting up the mock client...\n\nI need to define MockCcrClient within the acceptance test file since test helpers aren't shared across modules. Now I'm writing the message rendering functions for the CLI bridge module—these will handle displaying remote control status, session URLs, and lifecycle updates to the user.\n\nSetting up the integration tests next, where I'll configure mock client responses for different scenarios like successful archive creation and expired session handling. Writing test cases... Writing test assertions...\n\nI'm realizing the acceptance criteria specifically mentions session IDs round-tripping through the compatibility adapter at the transport layer, but since the application crate can't depend on remote-runtime, I should focus on testing the service-level contract instead—verifying that session IDs are preserved end-to-end at the service boundary rather than testing the internal transport normalization functions. I'm realizing the acceptance tests should live in the application crate as a unified suite that covers the service-level contract, integration scenarios, and CLI behavior all together, rather than scattering them across multiple files.\n\nWriting acceptance tests...","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1935,"cache_read_input_tokens":64482,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1935,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"aadda8d2-45d5-4dd3-ab70-25e42d8ce2e4","uuid":"577513f7-4777-415f-bd2d-c0bd9f2a930f"}
