{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01Mk7rRaKLccYZunCdSuN95L","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The functions in `bridge.rs` will trigger dead_code warnings since they're not called from outside the module yet. I should suppress them or make them pub and ensure clippy doesn't flag them as unused.\n\nThe cleanest fix for `-D warnings` compliance is to either:\n1. Add `#[allow(dead_code)]` to the module (since these are intended to be used in the future)\n2. Or mark the functions as `pub(crate)` and ensure they're referenced somewhere\n\nActually wait, the functions ARE `pub` already. But since `cmd/bridge.rs` is included as `pub mod bridge` but nothing in `main.rs` actually calls these pub functions, they'll show as dead code.\n \nI realize `dead_code` is a rustc lint, not a clippy lint, so `-D warnings` will turn it into an error. The cleanest approach is adding `#[allow(dead_code)]` at the module level in `bridge.rs` since these functions are intentionally public for future use. and trust that since they're pub in a pub module they won't trigger dead_code.\n\nActually wait - `pub` functions in a `pub` module don't trigger dead_code by default in library crates. But since `crates/cli` is a binary crate (has a `main.rs`), unused pub functions DO trigger dead_code warnings.\n\nLooking at the warnings - these are dead_code warnings in bridge.rs. I need to either use the functions or suppress the warning.\n\nThe cleanest approach for this use case (functions that define the bridge mode CLI output contract, expected to be used in the future when the bridge CLI command is implemented) is to add `#[allow(dead_code)]` at the top of the module. But that might look messy.\n\nAlternatively, I could export these from the `cmd` module so they're accessible but add `pub use bridge::*` or just make them available as a utility module.\n\nActually, the simplest fix that makes semantic sense: these are utility functions in a `pub mod bridge` that's part of the CLI module. In a binary crate, even pub items that are never called trigger dead_code. The standard approach is to allow dead_code for this module since it's a rendering utility module. The tests do call these functions, so they're not completely unused - they're just not reachable from main through non-test code. I should add `#[allow(dead_code)]` at the module level to suppress the warnings since these functions define the bridge CLI contract for future use. I'm realizing the cleanest approach is to just suppress the dead code warning at the module level in `bridge.rs` since these rendering utilities are part of an in-progress feature, rather than trying to artificially use them elsewhere or worry about unnecessary allow attributes.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":468,"cache_read_input_tokens":79574,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":468,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"aadda8d2-45d5-4dd3-ab70-25e42d8ce2e4","uuid":"829582d3-46f6-43c0-84ac-6b47043f27c5"}
